title.narrative: Indonesia Urban Water, Sanitation and Hygiene Penyehatan Lingkungan Untuk Semua (IUWASH PLUS)

description.narrative: (Indonesia): Eighty percent of Indonesians struggle to access piped water. Across the country, approximately 100,000 children die from diarrhea each year. The consequences of poor water, sanitation, and hygiene (WASH) services are felt most acutely by low-income families in urban areas. Through the Water for the World Act, the U.S. Government is helping improve WASH conditions in Indonesia, a priority country for USAID. Indonesia is committed to achieving 100 percent universal access to safe water and proper sanitation in alignment with the 2030 United Nations Sustainable Development Goals for both water and sanitation. Through the 5.5-year (2016-2021), $48,357,584 million USAID IUWASH PLUS project (including a $4.5 million contribution from the Government of Switzerland), USAID is building Indonesia's capacity to reduce barriers to safely-managed water and sanitation services. .USAID IUWASH PLUS works with governmental and donor agencies, the private sector, NGOs, service utilities and communities to strengthen the overall WASH 'ecosystem' in urban Indonesia. USAID through IUWASH PLUS strengthens the capacity of the providers of water and sanitation services to ensure that improved access is maintained over the long term. These partnerships are lowering the costs of WASH services for the most vulnerable Indonesians, contributing to life-saving gains in access and reducing the threat of waterborne diseases. Through IUWASH PLUS, USAID contributes to the Indo-Pacific strategy to improve natural resources management and to the U.S. Mission objective of supporting Indonesia's model of good governance practices to promote the development of a healthy, educated, and skilled population to drive inclusive economic growth...
